I'm trying to think how you could do this without something super complicated. If there was a way you could run a race without needing to actually run it first, that'd be the first thing. 
Otherwise, I would say that completing a race would have to generate some sort of key that only the sever could validate. But that already fails the sniff test since whatever generates a key already has control to do whatever

Hmm right and each racer can't have their own deterministic path where they aren't interacting with each other? Like that this racer will have a 1m13s lap and this racer will have a 1m8s lap? Trying to think how you could determine who would win based on what hazards are in their lane

Right, yeah, I get what you mean. What about the things you can control? Like, could you realistically determine a racer's lap time based off of the obstacles that are in their path? Or powerups they might get? Imagine each racer had an array of things that influence their base time of say 1m a lap. The hope would be being able to just sum values up and whomever has the lowest is the winner. 
Otherwise, yeah, you would have to generate seeds ahead of time for each race and randomly select between them
And each time you change something, you would have to regenerate those seeds

Gotcha. Yeah, the only other thing I can think of is going full multiplayer game mode and have the state of each racer tracked on a given tick rate. So long as nobody disconnects during the race everyone can post back each tick the position of each racer. 
Then you just have to trust that the entire lobby is in cheating and that they're all telling you the correct positions. It's really just a microcosm of the cat and mouse game multiplayer games deal with.
Right, so how is the race telling the server who won?
Oh, now we're building a VM to start up and run and then record itself and fill one cool hole? That's A lot more involved lol
I'm not sure I follow lol. Coolhole is a web sever with WebSockets. Your VM/race instance would have to directly communicate to Coolhole, which isn't something we have.
Yeah I know and I shouldnt expect you to sorry. I just mean it's the only mechanism coolholes sever can receive input is through the web sockets users use to say chat or add videos
Yeah we have it on an Ubuntu machine along with the db
But even if we had some node app running on that machine along with it, we would still have to build a way for it to communicate with cool hole that wasn't the typical WebSockets
Further the machine is pretty small. It's got no GPU and i think under 16gb of ram
You can build a stream and send m3u8s

Then browsers know that they should be getting more data. But I don't think necessarily putting the stream into Coolhole is the problem. It's the race communicating with the sever still. 
There's more potential for really janky implementations if they're on the same server, like the race application writing to a file and coolhole polling that file every five to ten minutes or so or something. But it's far from ideal there
